the invention of searching the
internet is fantastic for me

00:54:42.904 --> 00:54:44.820
because I can find this
paper, and this paper,

00:54:44.820 --> 00:54:45.945
and all that kind of thing.

00:54:45.945 --> 00:54:48.137
It's greatly improved
my job massively.

00:54:48.137 --> 00:54:49.970
On the other hand, if
you read, for example,

00:54:49.970 --> 00:54:51.890
"The Financial Times," their
employment correspondent,

00:54:51.890 --> 00:54:54.223
Sarah O'Connor, who's written
a series of articles about

00:54:54.223 --> 00:54:56.630
the Amazon warehouse, where
the invention of technology--

00:54:56.630 --> 00:54:58.970
the software for sort
of monitoring workers--

00:54:58.970 --> 00:55:00.900
seems to be
de-humanizing workers.

00:55:00.900 --> 00:55:03.030
I'm putting words
into [INAUDIBLE]..

00:55:03.030 --> 00:55:05.000
And these workers in
the Amazon warehouse

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.914
are really having
quite a difficult time.

00:55:07.914 --> 00:55:09.830
Part of what your question
is pointing to is I

00:55:09.830 --> 00:55:12.740
think an age-old question
about whether technology

00:55:12.740 --> 00:55:14.990
might be a liberating
force for some workers,

00:55:14.990 --> 00:55:16.520
stopping them from
routine tasks,

00:55:16.520 --> 00:55:20.120
but then might be particularly
bad and oppressive

00:55:20.120 --> 00:55:21.390
for other types as well.

00:55:21.390 --> 00:55:23.679
That's a tough issue,
very tough issue.

00:55:27.412 --> 00:55:28.870
AUDIENCE: It seems,
at least to me,

00:55:28.870 --> 00:55:31.671
that the entertainment sector is
becoming a lot more intangible

00:55:31.671 --> 00:55:32.170
as well.

00:55:32.170 --> 00:55:35.760
For example, if I cancel my
cable subscription and web

00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:39.330
surf instead, it seems
a lot harder to measure.

00:55:39.330 --> 00:55:41.070
We do have ads and so forth.

00:55:41.070 --> 00:55:45.720
But I was curious, do you
think this is happening?

00:55:45.720 --> 00:55:47.520
If so, how can we
kind of measure

00:55:47.520 --> 00:55:50.389
this extremely intangible
entertainment value

00:55:50.389 --> 00:55:52.680
that people are getting
through all these hours they're

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:56.500
web surfing on social
media and so forth?

00:55:56.500 --> 00:55:58.265
STIAN WESTLAKE: Do
you want to take that?

00:55:58.265 --> 00:55:59.640
JONATHAN HASKEL:
I mean, again, I

00:55:59.640 --> 00:56:02.700
think that's in the box of
a hard, hard measurement

00:56:02.700 --> 00:56:06.580
question, which people are
sort of struggling with.

00:56:06.580 --> 00:56:08.842
But you're right, the
entertainment industry--

00:56:08.842 --> 00:56:10.800
I mean, I think the way
that we think about it,

00:56:10.800 --> 00:56:12.220
but we see intangibles
everywhere,

00:56:12.220 --> 00:56:14.410
is this just bundle
of intangible assets.

00:56:14.410 --> 00:56:17.419
We talk in the book, for
example, about Harry Potter.

00:56:17.419 --> 00:56:18.960
As I was mentioning
before, Britain's

00:56:18.960 --> 00:56:20.910
most famous innovation
in many ways.

00:56:20.910 --> 00:56:23.160
It's not only the
script, but it's also

00:56:23.160 --> 00:56:24.360
the computer graphics.

00:56:24.360 --> 00:56:26.570
It's the set design and
all those kinds of things.

00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:29.380
So it's that kind of
bundle of things together,

00:56:29.380 --> 00:56:32.455
which creates a particularly
valuable type of asset.

00:56:32.455 --> 00:56:34.080
But of course, that
has to be delivered

00:56:34.080 --> 00:56:35.896
to people's houses via
broadband and cable

00:56:35.896 --> 00:56:37.770
and all that kind of
thing, about which there

00:56:37.770 --> 00:56:41.010
are many ownership
types of arguments.

00:56:41.010 --> 00:56:44.030
So there's a big policy area
about the delivery of it

00:56:44.030 --> 00:56:44.950
as well.

00:56:44.950 --> 00:56:46.800
STIAN WESTLAKE:
And I think there's

00:56:46.800 --> 00:56:50.530
two interesting questions there
arising from this intangible--

00:56:50.530 --> 00:56:52.560
sort of the increasing
intangibility.

00:56:52.560 --> 00:56:54.150
One of which is
kind of, how do you

00:56:54.150 --> 00:56:56.040
measure the stuff that
doesn't get paid for?

00:56:56.040 --> 00:56:58.350
It's a kind of
measurement question.

00:56:58.350 --> 00:57:00.270
At the same time,
there's a question

00:57:00.270 --> 00:57:04.170
which rights holders
and creators would ask,

00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:11.010
which is, how do you get some
payment for things that people

00:57:11.010 --> 00:57:12.460
are consuming and are enjoying?

00:57:12.460 --> 00:57:14.084
Which is as much a
question, going back

00:57:14.084 --> 00:57:15.384
to this kind of contestedness.

00:57:15.384 --> 00:57:16.550
What are the terms of trade?

00:57:16.550 --> 00:57:17.460
What are the rules?

00:57:17.460 --> 00:57:19.900
What are the rules
of these markets?

00:57:19.900 --> 00:57:23.955
I think they're both
pretty pressing questions.

00:57:23.955 --> 00:57:24.830
SPEAKER 1: OK, great.

00:57:24.830 --> 00:57:26.550
Last question.

00:57:26.550 --> 00:57:28.800
AUDIENCE: This isn't going
to be a very good question.

00:57:28.800 --> 00:57:30.100
I have a couple random
thoughts in my head,

00:57:30.100 --> 00:57:31.170
but I'm wondering if you can--

00:57:31.170 --> 00:57:32.730
because the purpose
will be for you guys

00:57:32.730 --> 00:57:34.170
to help stitch them
together, point me out

00:57:34.170 --> 00:57:35.310
where I'm conflicted.

00:57:35.310 --> 00:57:40.170
So the first one is it seems
to me like a reasonable claim

00:57:40.170 --> 00:57:43.230
to make would be that as our
economy gets more developed,

00:57:43.230 --> 00:57:46.130
it's gotten more specialized.

00:57:46.130 --> 00:57:49.040
And it seems like as it
gets more specialized,

00:57:49.040 --> 00:57:55.570
the distance between
any two workers grows.

00:57:55.570 --> 00:57:58.380
So the job that I do and
the job that he does--

00:57:58.380 --> 00:58:01.124
I have no idea who this guy is--

00:58:01.124 --> 00:58:03.600
is probably
functionally different.

00:58:03.600 --> 00:58:06.390
I don't think I could come
in and do his job tomorrow.

00:58:06.390 --> 00:58:08.580
I don't think he could come
and do my job tomorrow,

00:58:08.580 --> 00:58:12.510
because the context required
to do our specific tasks

00:58:12.510 --> 00:58:15.900
is actually not that
close to each other.

00:58:15.900 --> 00:58:17.720
So it seems like
the more specialized

00:58:17.720 --> 00:58:21.377
the economy gets, the kind
of, like I say, distance--

00:58:21.377 --> 00:58:23.960
I don't know what I'm actually
measuring-- gets further apart.

00:58:23.960 --> 00:58:27.660
And what that means is that
communication and organization

00:58:27.660 --> 00:58:31.380
become a more important
skill in order

00:58:31.380 --> 00:58:34.290
to bind all these
things together.

00:58:34.290 --> 00:58:36.060
That was like one
random thought I had,

00:58:36.060 --> 00:58:37.710
if you guys had sort of
thought about the problem

00:58:37.710 --> 00:58:38.710
from that point of view.

00:58:38.710 --> 00:58:42.720
And then, the other was
that you guys have clearly

00:58:42.720 --> 00:58:44.880
put a lot of
thinking into funding

00:58:44.880 --> 00:58:49.470
at a government, like country
or even institutional level.

00:58:49.470 --> 00:58:51.990
But there's also an
individual level of funding

00:58:51.990 --> 00:58:54.540
that has to happen, where
I have to decide to go

00:58:54.540 --> 00:58:56.370
get a particular degree or not.

00:58:56.370 --> 00:58:59.940
And I decide, even within
that degree, what happens.

00:58:59.940 --> 00:59:03.270
And so this other point
about specialization

00:59:03.270 --> 00:59:06.399
is the more specialized
things become,

00:59:06.399 --> 00:59:08.190
some of those things,
some of those choices

00:59:08.190 --> 00:59:12.060
to become specialized
require very advanced funding

00:59:12.060 --> 00:59:13.740
on the part of the individual.

00:59:13.740 --> 00:59:16.920
And to the extent that
our economy is maximized

00:59:16.920 --> 00:59:20.250
by reconfiguring
all these jobs, that

00:59:20.250 --> 00:59:22.770
can be a total bummer
if you guess wrong

00:59:22.770 --> 00:59:26.930
or it can be a lottery
ticket if you guess right.

00:59:26.930 --> 00:59:29.430
And then, the other point is--

00:59:29.430 --> 00:59:31.764
back to the one that you
made with technology,

00:59:31.764 --> 00:59:33.930
is that the other force
that technology can do is it

00:59:33.930 --> 00:59:37.320
can actually reduce the training
required to accomplish a job.

00:59:37.320 --> 00:59:38.820
And that actually
means the job pays

00:59:38.820 --> 00:59:41.550
less than it did before my
individual investment was

00:59:41.550 --> 00:59:42.150
lower.

00:59:42.150 --> 00:59:44.790
So I'm wondering if you
guys see trends in--

00:59:44.790 --> 00:59:48.210
or I don't know,
solutions in the sort

00:59:48.210 --> 00:59:52.105
of level of individuals
making these investments.

00:59:52.105 --> 00:59:54.480
And whether those things are
going in the right direction

00:59:54.480 --> 00:59:55.350
or not?

00:59:55.350 --> 00:59:56.700
So like I said, this
wasn't a good question.

00:59:56.700 --> 00:59:57.574
I admit that upfront.

00:59:57.574 --> 01:00:00.000
But some thoughts that
you guys [INAUDIBLE]..

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:01.020
STIAN WESTLAKE: Yeah.

01:00:01.020 --> 01:00:02.436
I think that's
really interesting.

01:00:02.436 --> 01:00:03.480
I mean, I think we've--

01:00:03.480 --> 01:00:06.030
on that second
question about, well,

01:00:06.030 --> 01:00:09.630
what's an individual to do
in terms of their own skills

01:00:09.630 --> 01:00:13.356
and training in
this new economy?

01:00:13.356 --> 01:00:15.855
I think the first thing, this
question about how specialized

01:00:15.855 --> 01:00:17.540
do you need to be?

01:00:17.540 --> 01:00:20.510
On the one hand, clearly the
demands of new technology

01:00:20.510 --> 01:00:23.180
do increase the premium to
certain highly-specialized

01:00:23.180 --> 01:00:24.710
skills.

01:00:24.710 --> 01:00:26.480
Everyone is hiring
data scientists.

01:00:26.480 --> 01:00:30.500
So next year, it'll be
something else and so forth.

01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:32.450
The flip-side is--
and it comes back

01:00:32.450 --> 01:00:34.550
to these properties of
intangibles, particularly

01:00:34.550 --> 01:00:36.620
the spillovers
and the synergies.

01:00:36.620 --> 01:00:39.230
We know that one thing that
will be really rewarded

01:00:39.230 --> 01:00:41.330
in an intangible
economy is the ability

01:00:41.330 --> 01:00:43.160
to bring together
different intangibles

01:00:43.160 --> 01:00:45.010
and kind of coordinate them.

01:00:45.010 --> 01:00:49.179
And that suggests that not so
much technical specialization,

01:00:49.179 --> 01:00:51.220
but actually a lot of
quite old-fashioned skills,

01:00:51.220 --> 01:00:55.090
like social skills, leadership,
and perhaps a combination

01:00:55.090 --> 01:00:57.490
of a sufficient level
of technical expertise

01:00:57.490 --> 01:01:00.130
plus an ability to be
kind of an integrator,

01:01:00.130 --> 01:01:02.504
might be really valuable.

01:01:02.504 --> 01:01:04.420
In my days when I was a
management consultant,

01:01:04.420 --> 01:01:06.725
I had this awful phrase
called "spiky integrators."

01:01:06.725 --> 01:01:08.350
I don't know if that's
a general thing.

01:01:08.350 --> 01:01:10.330
But it'd be someone who's
got a spike in one area,

01:01:10.330 --> 01:01:11.890
but enough competence
in other areas

01:01:11.890 --> 01:01:13.482
to integrate different skills.

01:01:13.482 --> 01:01:15.940
And it may be that in an economy
of more synergies and more

01:01:15.940 --> 01:01:19.480
spillovers, those skills
are particularly valued.

01:01:19.480 --> 01:01:21.760
I know in my old
work, we did a lot

01:01:21.760 --> 01:01:23.830
of research asking
hiring companies

01:01:23.830 --> 01:01:26.350
about the skills they were
looking for in data scientists.

01:01:26.350 --> 01:01:28.162
And that was the
kind of sweet spot.

01:01:28.162 --> 01:01:30.370
It was, we want people who
are enough of a quant jock

01:01:30.370 --> 01:01:33.430
to understand what's going on,
but they also need to be able--

01:01:33.430 --> 01:01:35.350
and then, the company
would reel off

01:01:35.350 --> 01:01:36.970
five different
things they needed

01:01:36.970 --> 01:01:40.060
to understand related to their
own particular business model.

01:01:40.060 --> 01:01:42.130
Now, in some ways,
that's quite good news

01:01:42.130 --> 01:01:45.680
for our kind of hypothetical,
perplexed young person

01:01:45.680 --> 01:01:46.180
setting out.

01:01:46.180 --> 01:01:48.980
Because it means that there are
some more transferable skills

01:01:48.980 --> 01:01:50.790
that are worth developing.

01:01:50.790 --> 01:01:53.050
Often, quite soft skills.

01:01:53.050 --> 01:01:55.870
But then, I kind of do
agree with your more--

01:01:55.870 --> 01:01:59.990
the more concerned part
of what you're saying.

01:01:59.990 --> 01:02:01.930
Because if we are
expecting people

01:02:01.930 --> 01:02:04.450
to invest more in their
skills, this uncertainty

01:02:04.450 --> 01:02:07.460
still applies because some of
these skills will be specific.

01:02:07.460 --> 01:02:09.501
And I guess there, this
is the question of, well,

01:02:09.501 --> 01:02:11.890
how do you genuinely
generate lifelong learning

01:02:11.890 --> 01:02:12.880
in an economy?

01:02:12.880 --> 01:02:14.980
Well, most world
economies, learning

01:02:14.980 --> 01:02:18.790
stops at 18, or 21, or 25.

01:02:18.790 --> 01:02:21.675
I think that's partly a
technological question

01:02:21.675 --> 01:02:25.355
and partly a social question.

01:02:25.355 --> 01:02:27.480
JONATHAN HASKEL: Can I try
a very quick reflection?

01:02:27.480 --> 01:02:28.390
Would it be all right?

01:02:28.390 --> 01:02:29.040
SPEAKER 1: Sure.

01:02:29.040 --> 01:02:30.873
JONATHAN HASKEL: Just
on your nice question,

01:02:30.873 --> 01:02:32.740
as a card-carrying
economist, I think

01:02:32.740 --> 01:02:34.570
you asked a very
profound question, which

01:02:34.570 --> 01:02:37.660
is, if you think about
societies before they

01:02:37.660 --> 01:02:39.280
were very specialized.

01:02:39.280 --> 01:02:42.490
You know, the farmer
would know the farm worker

01:02:42.490 --> 01:02:43.180
and they would--

01:02:43.180 --> 01:02:45.035
you do me a favor,
and you a favor,

01:02:45.035 --> 01:02:46.160
and all that kind of thing.

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:48.500
But once you get a very
specialized economy,

01:02:48.500 --> 01:02:51.411
and the distance between
people goes apart,

01:02:51.411 --> 01:02:53.410
there isn't so now I'm
going to be an economist.

01:02:53.410 --> 01:02:55.420
There's just a shortage of love.

01:02:55.420 --> 01:02:57.190
That's the problem.

01:02:57.190 --> 01:02:59.380
There's just not enough
love to go around.

01:02:59.380 --> 01:03:02.230
And so we have to have
in society some way

01:03:02.230 --> 01:03:03.100
to replace that.

01:03:03.100 --> 01:03:04.930
And it's called
the price system.

01:03:04.930 --> 01:03:07.210
And the miracle of
economics is that

01:03:07.210 --> 01:03:09.730
this incredible
decentralized economy where

01:03:09.730 --> 01:03:12.287
people don't know each
other is coordinated

01:03:12.287 --> 01:03:13.120
by the price system.

01:03:13.120 --> 01:03:15.250
So the shoes you're wearing,
you don't know the person

01:03:15.250 --> 01:03:16.030
who's built the shoes.

01:03:16.030 --> 01:03:18.550
Hundreds of years ago, you
would know who's made the shoes.

01:03:18.550 --> 01:03:19.750
But you don't know that now.

01:03:19.750 --> 01:03:21.970
Now, of course, in the
intangible economy,

01:03:21.970 --> 01:03:25.089
for the types of reasons
we've talked about,

01:03:25.089 --> 01:03:27.130
maybe the price system
just doesn't work so well.

01:03:27.130 --> 01:03:28.838
So we don't quite know
what the ownership

01:03:28.838 --> 01:03:29.854
is, as Stian was saying.

01:03:29.854 --> 01:03:32.270
We don't quite know about the
spillovers, and all of that.

01:03:32.270 --> 01:03:36.084
So I think we need to possibly
reinvent all of that stuff,

01:03:36.084 --> 01:03:37.750
because we may not
have the right system

01:03:37.750 --> 01:03:40.789
to deal with it at the moment.

01:03:40.789 --> 01:03:42.080
SPEAKER 1: Thank you, Jonathan.

01:03:42.080 --> 01:03:42.790
Stian.

01:03:42.790 --> 01:03:44.260
Thank you, everyone, for coming.

01:03:44.260 --> 01:03:45.385
JONATHAN HASKEL: Thank you.

